        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The expected linewidths could range from 2-3 to 30 km/s, therefore, a resolution of 1 km/s is well suited to spectrally resolve the lines (10 to 30 spectral resolution elements). 
We have selected a spectral averaging of 2 to lower the data rate.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The expected brightness distibutions should arise from components, extending over a radius of 14", with clump sizes of 6-7". Emission from the molecular ring at ~14" is expected for SiC2 and the low frequency line of SiC. The requested angular resolution should be enough to resolve the structures at large and medium distances from the star. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For the sensitivity we have used the weakest line of Si2C obtaining a conservative value for the S/N ratio of 5 considering a uniform distribution of 5". The intensitity could be higher in case that the emitting region is smaller or clumpy as for SiC2. If needed, we could degradate the angular resolution to improve the S/N, although we are confident that Si2C could be detected with S/N&gt;5 with the proposed settings at these frequencies. For the rest of the lines proposed we expect a S/N&gt;20.
The bandwith selected allow us to detect several lines of the proposed molecules.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We exceed the data rate by 0.21 MB/s. We have already selected spectral averaging of 2.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We would like to have the largest velocity resolution to study the emission at different distances from the star. Single polarization offers this possibility maintaining a broad frequency coverage.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SINGLE_POLARISATION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
