        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In the particular case of the inner regions, where the gas is accelerated up to v~5 km*s-1, the linewidths should be less or equal to 10 km*s-1. A resolution of ~0.7 km/s is well suited to spectrally resolve the lines (up to 14 spectral resolution elements). </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The expected brightness distibutions should arise from compact components at these frequencies (up to r=3-5") in the inner regions of the CSE. The requested angular resolution should be enough to provide high spatial resolution in this inner region. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For the sensitivity we have used line of SiC (237GHz) which has a peak intensity (at vlsr~0 with respect to the systemic velocity of the source) of 0.05 K in antenna temperature (Cernicharo, 1989). This value converted to Tmb is ~0.08 K. Considering an uniform distribution of 5" we obtain a flux of ~90 mJy. Therefore with the requested sensitivity we obtain a S/N of 45. 
This value could be higher if the SiC distribution is smaller or distributed in a ring structure at r=5". For Si2C at these frequencies the sensitivity could be limited (obtaining S/N~2), in that case we should degradate the angular and spectral resolution to improve S/N. 
For the rest of the lines proposed we expect S/N&gt;15-20.
The bandwith selected allow us to detect several lines of the proposed molecules.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
