    <prp:abstract>It is a fact that dust grains are ubiquitous in the interstellar medium. However, the formation of
these tiny particles, which takes place in the ejecta of evolved stars, remains poorly understood. The small angular scales on which dust formation occurs has prevented its study through observations in the past. The high angular resolution and sensitivity of ALMA brings the opportunity to shed light on the process of formation of dust grains from gas phase molecular seeds. We propose to observe, with unprecedented angular resolution and sensitivity, the brightness distribution of the main gas phase carriers of Si-C bonds (SiC2, SiC, and the recently discovered Si2C), and probable seeds of SiC dust grains, in the arquetype of carbon-rich envelope IRC+10216. We aim at characterizing their abundance gradients and constraining the role played by these gas phase seeds in the formation of SiC dust grains.</prp:abstract>
